WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.000
Hello, my name is Chelsea Parlette-Pellariti and today I want to talk to you about building

00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:18.680
machine learning web apps using Shiny for Python.

00:00:18.680 --> 00:00:22.260
Now it sounds like you heard a little bit about this before, of course, from all the

00:00:22.260 --> 00:00:27.200
other wonderful Shiny talks we have, but just to review, Shiny for Python is a tool that

00:00:27.200 --> 00:00:34.340
allows you to build interactive, reactive, and scalable web apps that just work with

00:00:34.340 --> 00:00:40.680
the already rich machine learning ecosystem that exists in Python.

00:00:40.680 --> 00:00:45.959
So throughout this talk, I'm going to share some examples of how I've used Shiny for Python

00:00:45.959 --> 00:00:50.840
in my machine learning workflow, and I just want you to ask yourself, where could Shiny

00:00:50.840 --> 00:00:56.020
for Python fit into your machine learning workflow?

00:00:56.020 --> 00:01:02.099
Now I'm not coming to you today as a developer who could give an incredibly complex and detailed

00:01:02.099 --> 00:01:07.620
talk about the inner workings of Shiny for Python and exactly how it's implemented.

00:01:07.620 --> 00:01:13.379
Rather, I'm coming to you as a Shiny for Python user, and I want to tell you what that experience

00:01:13.379 --> 00:01:19.660
is like so that you can see if it's something that you want to implement in your own workflow.

00:01:19.660 --> 00:01:24.580
So why am I giving you this talk if I'm not a Shiny for Python developer?

00:01:25.139 --> 00:01:26.339
Well, let me set the scene.

00:01:26.339 --> 00:01:34.220
So it's last year before our StudioConf, and none of you knew that Shiny for Python was

00:01:34.220 --> 00:01:39.900
going to be announced, but I did because I spent the summer working with the developer

00:01:39.900 --> 00:01:45.639
team to build apps and create educational materials to help people learn how to use

00:01:45.639 --> 00:01:46.639
Shiny for Python.

00:01:46.639 --> 00:01:52.940
In fact, if you go to the Shiny for Python front page, you might see one of my apps on

00:01:52.940 --> 00:01:56.860
that front page, like this one.

00:01:56.860 --> 00:01:59.820
But more than that, I'm a professor.

00:01:59.820 --> 00:02:05.099
And while a lot of you probably don't spend your day-to-day time in front of dozens of

00:02:05.099 --> 00:02:12.820
undergrads, I think as data people, a huge part of what we do is teach.

00:02:12.820 --> 00:02:19.899
Because what is teaching but explaining complicated, complex, and difficult topics in a way that

00:02:19.899 --> 00:02:23.059
is easily digestible?

00:02:23.059 --> 00:02:28.220
And I found through my teaching that Shiny for Python apps really helped me accomplish

00:02:28.220 --> 00:02:33.860
that goal of communicating difficult things in an easily digestible way.

00:02:33.860 --> 00:02:38.059
For instance, here's an example of an app that I use in my deep learning class.

00:02:38.059 --> 00:02:42.699
This is demonstrating a certain method that goes with computer vision models that basically

00:02:42.699 --> 00:02:48.460
tells you what about an image was important to the computer vision model in classifying

00:02:48.460 --> 00:02:49.460
that image.

00:02:50.020 --> 00:02:53.259
So here we see a picture of some elephants, and you can see that the model thinks that

00:02:53.259 --> 00:02:54.259
these are elephants.

00:02:54.259 --> 00:02:59.220
And on the right, you get a heat map showing you exactly what pixels were important in

00:02:59.220 --> 00:03:01.899
making that classification of elephant.

00:03:01.899 --> 00:03:06.580
And here you can see it's things that make sense, right, like ears and trunks.

00:03:06.580 --> 00:03:13.339
And using Shiny for Python apps allows me to get my students involved and to interact

00:03:13.339 --> 00:03:16.139
with the material that we're learning.

00:03:17.100 --> 00:03:19.580
Now Shiny as a framework is not new.

00:03:19.580 --> 00:03:27.059
As a lot of you know, Shiny came out in 2012 for R. And in the next about 10 years, it

00:03:27.059 --> 00:03:32.660
has become a beloved tool for making web apps in the R community.

00:03:32.660 --> 00:03:38.619
Now last year, Shiny for Python was announced, and I think that just means that the community

00:03:38.619 --> 00:03:44.899
of people that is about to fall in love with Shiny just expanded.

00:03:44.899 --> 00:03:50.100
Now I mentioned before that I'm a professor, but if you force me to put a label on myself,

00:03:50.100 --> 00:03:52.539
I would call myself a statistician.

00:03:52.539 --> 00:03:58.179
So as you can imagine, I fell in love with R and all its associated tools very early

00:03:58.179 --> 00:04:00.339
in my career.

00:04:00.339 --> 00:04:07.259
But I currently teach in an engineering department, which means I am forced to teach all of my

00:04:07.259 --> 00:04:09.500
classes in Python.

00:04:09.500 --> 00:04:11.500
The prereqs are in Python.

00:04:11.500 --> 00:04:13.860
The classes after mine are in Python.

00:04:13.860 --> 00:04:18.299
And just to be honest, a lot of my students are more comfortable in Python.

00:04:18.299 --> 00:04:24.059
And I think that might be relatable to a lot of you, maybe your web developers, your boss,

00:04:24.059 --> 00:04:28.540
your whole team, your engineers, someone else uses Python.

00:04:28.540 --> 00:04:30.660
And so now you have to.

00:04:30.660 --> 00:04:35.100
And the beauty of Shiny for Python is that we can use the Shiny framework, which a lot

00:04:35.100 --> 00:04:39.779
of us may have fallen in love with when we were using it in R, and we can leverage it

00:04:39.779 --> 00:04:44.220
with all of the power that Python has.

00:04:44.220 --> 00:04:50.339
And I joke a little bit about being forced to teach in Python, but I have to admit, Python

00:04:50.339 --> 00:04:57.820
has a great industry standard, very rich ecosystem of machine learning packages like scikit-learn,

00:04:57.820 --> 00:05:00.779
TensorFlow, Keras, and Pandas.

00:05:00.779 --> 00:05:06.100
And now we can leverage the power of these very established machine learning packages

00:05:06.339 --> 00:05:09.779
with the Shiny framework using Shiny for Python.

00:05:11.540 --> 00:05:17.940
So I want to tell you about three different times you might want to use Shiny for Python

00:05:17.940 --> 00:05:19.940
in your machine learning workflow.

00:05:19.940 --> 00:05:23.299
And the first time is when you need interactivity.

00:05:24.339 --> 00:05:31.619
Now, as a professor, I know that interactivity is key to deep understanding.

00:05:32.179 --> 00:05:38.739
Look, sometimes your boss or the CEO just wants a one-line memo telling them what to do,

00:05:38.739 --> 00:05:43.220
or they want a Word document with the information that you have found.

00:05:43.220 --> 00:05:50.739
But in cases where deep understanding is the goal, interactivity is going to be key for that.

00:05:50.739 --> 00:05:54.179
And Shiny for Python can provide that interactivity for you.

00:05:55.059 --> 00:05:58.980
For instance, here's an example of an app that I use with my students to teach them

00:05:58.980 --> 00:06:02.179
about the differences between different classification models.

00:06:02.739 --> 00:06:06.579
As you can see on the screen, there's a bunch of different things that my students can change.

00:06:06.579 --> 00:06:08.980
They can change the data set they're looking at,

00:06:08.980 --> 00:06:12.100
and they can change different hyperparameters for our various models.

00:06:12.739 --> 00:06:16.899
Those are then going to interact with the graphs that are shown on the web page,

00:06:16.899 --> 00:06:23.220
and it allows them to explore and ask questions about these different classification models,

00:06:23.220 --> 00:06:26.420
and therefore engage and get a deeper understanding

00:06:26.420 --> 00:06:29.859
of how these models make classifications differently.

00:06:32.019 --> 00:06:36.820
Another app that I use is this app that helps you look at and assess

00:06:36.820 --> 00:06:40.339
model calibration and the fairness of different models.

00:06:40.899 --> 00:06:46.179
Especially with this topic, it's really important if you want people to have a deep understanding

00:06:46.820 --> 00:06:54.100
to let them ask and then answer their own questions as they engage and as they get curious.

00:06:54.100 --> 00:06:58.739
And that's what interactivity through a Shiny for Python app allows you to do.

00:07:01.220 --> 00:07:03.540
And we've seen apps like this before.

00:07:03.540 --> 00:07:08.420
This is another one that I use to explain item response theory models.

00:07:08.420 --> 00:07:12.899
And you can see it has your typical input sliders that affect a graph.

00:07:12.899 --> 00:07:17.299
But another thing that I really love is we don't just have to change

00:07:17.299 --> 00:07:19.619
graphs in response to user input.

00:07:19.619 --> 00:07:24.260
For instance, in this app, the actual text explanation of the model

00:07:24.260 --> 00:07:28.980
dynamically updates as the users change their different parameters.

00:07:28.980 --> 00:07:33.540
This again allows them to get curious, ask questions about what happens when

00:07:33.540 --> 00:07:38.260
you change this parameter or that one, and then get the answers to their questions.

00:07:38.899 --> 00:07:42.660
So where might you have interactivity in your workflow?

00:07:42.660 --> 00:07:46.339
Well, in my humble opinion, it is in the three Ds.

00:07:46.339 --> 00:07:48.500
The first one is description.

00:07:48.500 --> 00:07:52.339
So when you have a new data set or you're trying to answer a new question,

00:07:52.339 --> 00:07:57.700
you might want to build a tool that allows your co-workers or your shareholders

00:07:57.700 --> 00:08:01.459
to explore the data and, like I mentioned before,

00:08:01.459 --> 00:08:06.019
ask and answer their own questions as they get curious about it.

00:08:06.019 --> 00:08:11.059
You can use Shiny for Python to build a very nice, well-working,

00:08:11.059 --> 00:08:16.260
no-code exploratory data analysis app that allows people to filter,

00:08:16.260 --> 00:08:19.459
plot, and summarize their data as they explore it.

00:08:20.660 --> 00:08:22.820
The second D is in development.

00:08:22.820 --> 00:08:25.940
As you're building models or comparing models,

00:08:25.940 --> 00:08:29.700
you can use Shiny for Python at all stages of that process.

00:08:29.700 --> 00:08:34.099
For instance, you could even build a Shiny app that helps people on your team

00:08:34.099 --> 00:08:36.500
build an actual machine learning model.

00:08:36.500 --> 00:08:39.539
Or you can use it as a way to compare different models

00:08:39.539 --> 00:08:43.059
as you're trying to decide what is going to get put in production.

00:08:43.059 --> 00:08:45.780
Or even do something like a multiverse analysis

00:08:45.780 --> 00:08:49.780
in which you look at the effect of different modeling choices

00:08:49.780 --> 00:08:54.179
and how it might impact the inferences or the predictions that you're making.

00:08:55.539 --> 00:08:57.700
And the last D is deployment.

00:08:57.700 --> 00:09:00.500
Now, the other two bullet points talked about times

00:09:00.580 --> 00:09:05.619
when you're in that model development or exploration process.

00:09:05.619 --> 00:09:09.859
But you can also use Shiny for Python once your model is completely settled on

00:09:09.859 --> 00:09:12.099
and you're just deploying it to users.

00:09:12.099 --> 00:09:16.260
For instance, a Shiny for Python web app makes an excellent front end

00:09:16.260 --> 00:09:18.900
for something like a recommendation system.

00:09:18.900 --> 00:09:20.659
And because it's interactive,

00:09:20.659 --> 00:09:25.460
it allows your users to have a richer experience with your model

00:09:25.460 --> 00:09:28.419
because they're not just getting one static prediction.

00:09:30.979 --> 00:09:34.900
So another time that you might consider using Shiny for Python apps

00:09:34.900 --> 00:09:37.219
is when you need reactivity.

00:09:38.739 --> 00:09:40.179
Now, what is reactivity?

00:09:40.179 --> 00:09:41.780
Well, to take a step back,

00:09:41.780 --> 00:09:44.260
one thing I think we can all agree on

00:09:44.260 --> 00:09:48.179
is that machine learning is computationally expensive.

00:09:48.179 --> 00:09:52.580
Whether we're doing training, fine tuning, making inferences,

00:09:52.580 --> 00:09:56.979
a lot of the things that we're doing take a lot of computational power.

00:09:56.979 --> 00:10:01.380
And so we don't want an app that is going to run top to bottom

00:10:01.380 --> 00:10:03.460
every time a user changes something.

00:10:03.460 --> 00:10:07.859
Because sometimes, in fact, I might even venture to say oftentimes,

00:10:07.859 --> 00:10:11.940
you are going to be doing things that are computationally expensive

00:10:11.940 --> 00:10:13.700
when building machine learning apps.

00:10:14.260 --> 00:10:16.900
So reactivity basically refers to the fact

00:10:16.900 --> 00:10:20.340
that we are going to minimally re-render our apps.

00:10:20.340 --> 00:10:23.940
Only things that absolutely need to change and be re-run

00:10:23.940 --> 00:10:27.299
are going to be changed in response to user input.

00:10:28.900 --> 00:10:31.539
So here's the world's cutest app.

00:10:31.539 --> 00:10:34.099
This is looking at a computer vision model

00:10:34.099 --> 00:10:37.140
and it's basically allowing you to test out

00:10:37.140 --> 00:10:41.219
how different parts of the image are important to the model

00:10:41.219 --> 00:10:44.659
by seeing what happens when you completely cover it up.

00:10:44.659 --> 00:10:47.059
By the way, the takeaway from this screenshot

00:10:47.059 --> 00:10:51.380
is that if the computer vision model can't see the fluffy corgi butt,

00:10:51.380 --> 00:10:55.059
it is less confident that the image is a corgi.

00:10:55.059 --> 00:10:57.059
Okay, back to the app though.

00:10:57.859 --> 00:11:00.340
This has a bunch of user inputs.

00:11:00.340 --> 00:11:02.979
For instance, it allows users to upload an image

00:11:02.979 --> 00:11:04.820
that they can then use with this app.

00:11:05.460 --> 00:11:07.059
When someone uploads an image,

00:11:07.059 --> 00:11:11.059
pretty much everything on the right-hand side of this app has to update, right?

00:11:11.059 --> 00:11:12.500
We need to update the picture.

00:11:12.500 --> 00:11:14.580
We need to update the occluded picture.

00:11:14.580 --> 00:11:16.260
And we need to make predictions

00:11:16.260 --> 00:11:19.380
both for the unoccluded and the occluded image.

00:11:20.020 --> 00:11:22.020
However, if you look at the other inputs,

00:11:22.020 --> 00:11:25.380
we can also decide what is going to be occluded in the image,

00:11:25.380 --> 00:11:28.739
like what range of pixels are going to be removed.

00:11:28.739 --> 00:11:30.099
And when we change that,

00:11:30.900 --> 00:11:33.859
we don't need to update the original image

00:11:33.859 --> 00:11:37.460
and we don't need to update the model's original prediction

00:11:37.460 --> 00:11:41.380
because nothing about our user input actually affects that.

00:11:41.380 --> 00:11:45.299
And so we're saving the computational expense of updating that

00:11:45.299 --> 00:11:48.500
by using reactivity by saying,

00:11:48.500 --> 00:11:52.580
only re-render things that actually need to be re-rendered.

00:11:54.340 --> 00:11:57.380
Now, one thing that is really nice about Shiny

00:11:57.380 --> 00:11:59.460
is not just that you get reactivity

00:11:59.460 --> 00:12:01.700
because that's not unique to Shiny.

00:12:01.700 --> 00:12:05.539
One thing that is unique to Shiny is this inferred reactivity.

00:12:06.260 --> 00:12:08.820
Inferred reactivity basically refers to the idea

00:12:08.820 --> 00:12:12.820
that Shiny is deciding what needs to be re-rendered in your app

00:12:12.820 --> 00:12:14.580
based on how you wrote it.

00:12:14.659 --> 00:12:17.140
You don't have to think about that at all.

00:12:18.260 --> 00:12:20.500
In order to get a deeper idea of what I mean,

00:12:20.500 --> 00:12:22.900
let's look at this really silly demo app.

00:12:22.900 --> 00:12:25.619
Here we have an app that is plotting a scatterplot

00:12:25.619 --> 00:12:27.140
based on a sample of data.

00:12:27.140 --> 00:12:29.619
It lets users change various aesthetics.

00:12:29.619 --> 00:12:30.820
And then at the bottom left,

00:12:30.820 --> 00:12:33.380
it gives you a summary of the sample of your data.

00:12:34.979 --> 00:12:36.260
When we have this app,

00:12:36.260 --> 00:12:39.460
we basically have a computational graph

00:12:39.460 --> 00:12:42.179
that tells you about how all the different parts of the app

00:12:42.179 --> 00:12:43.539
are related to each other.

00:12:43.539 --> 00:12:46.020
For instance, we start off our app with some data.

00:12:46.900 --> 00:12:49.380
And then if we press the action button,

00:12:49.380 --> 00:12:51.140
we take a sample of that data.

00:12:52.099 --> 00:12:54.419
From that sample, we might rely on the fact

00:12:54.419 --> 00:12:56.340
that users are going to choose the color

00:12:56.340 --> 00:12:58.820
and what's on the y-axis of our scatterplot.

00:12:59.460 --> 00:13:02.580
And using that, we then build our scatterplot.

00:13:03.619 --> 00:13:05.460
Then of course, we have that summary table,

00:13:05.460 --> 00:13:09.140
which doesn't rely on the y variable for our plot

00:13:09.140 --> 00:13:11.299
or the color of the dots in our plot,

00:13:11.299 --> 00:13:12.659
but does rely on the sample

00:13:12.659 --> 00:13:14.580
that we've randomly taken from our data.

00:13:15.140 --> 00:13:18.419
Now, we just built a very simple computational graph.

00:13:18.419 --> 00:13:20.020
And you can see that this tells us

00:13:20.020 --> 00:13:22.659
how the different parts of the app relate to each other.

00:13:22.659 --> 00:13:26.419
For instance, if I update the dot color of my scatterplot,

00:13:26.419 --> 00:13:29.219
I have no need to update my summary table.

00:13:29.219 --> 00:13:30.739
And that's reflected in my graph.

00:13:31.299 --> 00:13:35.059
Only things downstream of changes that we make

00:13:35.059 --> 00:13:38.099
need to be updated when that input is updated.

00:13:38.979 --> 00:13:41.859
Now, this is an incredibly simple app

00:13:41.859 --> 00:13:44.500
and the computational graphs for your apps

00:13:44.500 --> 00:13:48.260
as they grow in complexity is going to become

00:13:48.979 --> 00:13:51.219
at some point unmanageable

00:13:51.219 --> 00:13:53.299
if you had to manage this yourself.

00:13:53.299 --> 00:13:57.059
But the good news is that Shiny manages it for you.

00:13:57.619 --> 00:14:00.099
So instead of you having to design

00:14:00.099 --> 00:14:03.299
and specify the computational graph for your app,

00:14:03.299 --> 00:14:06.820
Shiny is inferring what this computational graph should be.

00:14:06.820 --> 00:14:09.219
So you get to benefit from reactivity

00:14:09.219 --> 00:14:10.739
without having to think about

00:14:10.739 --> 00:14:12.900
the computational graph explicitly.

00:14:12.900 --> 00:14:15.940
And I know as I build more complicated apps,

00:14:15.940 --> 00:14:17.780
I am definitely going to mess up

00:14:17.780 --> 00:14:19.619
my computational graph at some point.

00:14:19.619 --> 00:14:21.380
So I'm very grateful that Shiny

00:14:21.380 --> 00:14:22.900
doesn't even make me think about it.

00:14:23.539 --> 00:14:25.460
And you can see with even this Corgi app

00:14:25.460 --> 00:14:27.780
that looks pretty simple when you look at it,

00:14:27.780 --> 00:14:31.299
the computational graph gets more and more complex

00:14:31.299 --> 00:14:33.299
as you add various functionality.

00:14:33.380 --> 00:14:37.619
So the last scenario when I think you might want

00:14:37.619 --> 00:14:40.580
to use Shiny for Python in your workflow

00:14:40.580 --> 00:14:43.219
is when you need scalability.

00:14:44.500 --> 00:14:46.900
Now, the nice thing about Shiny for Python

00:14:46.900 --> 00:14:50.500
is that it's good for all parts of the process.

00:14:50.500 --> 00:14:52.739
It allows you to have a smooth on-ramp

00:14:52.739 --> 00:14:54.900
to build really fast, simple,

00:14:54.900 --> 00:14:56.900
but really good looking apps.

00:14:56.900 --> 00:14:58.900
But it also is there to support you

00:14:58.900 --> 00:15:01.140
when that app becomes mission critical

00:15:01.140 --> 00:15:03.219
and you have to scale it up

00:15:03.219 --> 00:15:04.900
and get it ready for production.

00:15:06.020 --> 00:15:07.619
A lot of other web app frameworks

00:15:07.619 --> 00:15:10.260
focus on one portion of this process.

00:15:10.260 --> 00:15:12.979
There's a lot of great web app tools out there

00:15:12.979 --> 00:15:16.500
that allow you to spin up apps incredibly quickly

00:15:16.500 --> 00:15:18.659
and get a pretty good looking result.

00:15:19.219 --> 00:15:20.979
While others focus specifically

00:15:20.979 --> 00:15:23.380
on getting your apps ready for production

00:15:23.380 --> 00:15:26.979
when you need a very stable and good looking app

00:15:26.979 --> 00:15:29.059
that can be pinged,

00:15:29.780 --> 00:15:31.299
pinged, excuse me,

00:15:31.299 --> 00:15:33.619
millions of times a day by your users.

00:15:34.580 --> 00:15:36.659
But the nice thing about Shiny for Python

00:15:36.659 --> 00:15:38.020
is that it really can handle

00:15:38.020 --> 00:15:40.179
a lot of these different stages.

00:15:40.179 --> 00:15:43.780
For instance, it's great at spinning up really quick apps.

00:15:44.659 --> 00:15:46.340
At the last conference,

00:15:46.340 --> 00:15:48.179
Joe gave a talk where he mentioned

00:15:48.179 --> 00:15:50.580
that the idea for the Shiny framework

00:15:50.580 --> 00:15:53.539
basically came to him fully formed

00:15:53.539 --> 00:15:56.580
in a blink of an eye upon waking up.

00:15:56.580 --> 00:15:59.219
And he really built a web app framework

00:15:59.219 --> 00:16:01.539
that allows you to build apps in the same way.

00:16:02.340 --> 00:16:03.619
For instance, here's an example

00:16:03.619 --> 00:16:05.380
that I use in one of my classes

00:16:05.380 --> 00:16:08.179
that is basically a front end for Hangman

00:16:08.179 --> 00:16:09.700
and my students are responsible

00:16:09.700 --> 00:16:11.700
for building the backend.

00:16:11.700 --> 00:16:13.059
And just like Joe,

00:16:13.059 --> 00:16:16.260
this came to me as a fully formed idea one morning

00:16:16.260 --> 00:16:16.820
and I said,

00:16:16.820 --> 00:16:20.580
oh, I want my students to build Hangman today.

00:16:20.580 --> 00:16:21.859
And in about an hour,

00:16:21.859 --> 00:16:24.659
I was able to spin up this very simple Shiny app

00:16:24.659 --> 00:16:26.979
and have something that looked really good,

00:16:26.979 --> 00:16:28.260
especially given the fact

00:16:28.260 --> 00:16:30.580
that I only had about an hour to spend on it.

00:16:32.099 --> 00:16:34.099
And I'm a professor,

00:16:34.099 --> 00:16:38.979
I don't have time to build production level web apps.

00:16:38.979 --> 00:16:41.059
And using Shiny for Python

00:16:41.059 --> 00:16:43.059
allows me to build things like this,

00:16:43.059 --> 00:16:45.219
where I had an idea one morning,

00:16:45.219 --> 00:16:47.299
I spent a couple of hours building an app

00:16:47.299 --> 00:16:50.659
and my students literally used it that afternoon.

00:16:51.460 --> 00:16:54.979
And one of the tools that Shiny for Python offers you

00:16:54.979 --> 00:16:57.700
is actually something that was mentioned in the last talk,

00:16:57.700 --> 00:17:02.260
which is this serverless deployment via Shiny Live.

00:17:02.260 --> 00:17:04.500
So this is an example of that app

00:17:04.500 --> 00:17:05.540
that I showed you before

00:17:05.540 --> 00:17:07.459
with all of the classification models.

00:17:07.459 --> 00:17:10.260
And this is something that I've hosted with Shiny Live.

00:17:11.219 --> 00:17:14.579
Now, through the magic of WebAssembly and Pyedide,

00:17:14.579 --> 00:17:17.540
you can actually have these apps run

00:17:18.020 --> 00:17:20.819
in your client's browser

00:17:21.699 --> 00:17:25.060
without actually technically hosting the app anywhere.

00:17:25.939 --> 00:17:27.699
If you look at the screenshot,

00:17:27.699 --> 00:17:30.180
all of the information needed for the app,

00:17:30.180 --> 00:17:33.859
like the code, any data that's relevant to the app,

00:17:33.859 --> 00:17:36.020
is all encoded and stored

00:17:36.020 --> 00:17:39.540
in what is admittedly a very long URL.

00:17:39.540 --> 00:17:41.859
But by sending someone that URL,

00:17:41.859 --> 00:17:45.699
they're able to run the app in their browser locally.

00:17:45.699 --> 00:17:48.900
All they need is that URL and an internet connection.

00:17:49.859 --> 00:17:51.380
And what does that mean for you?

00:17:51.380 --> 00:17:53.619
Well, as the person deploying this app,

00:17:53.619 --> 00:17:55.459
it means no hosting costs

00:17:55.459 --> 00:17:58.500
because you're not actually hosting anything.

00:17:59.140 --> 00:18:01.939
For your users, that means they do not have to worry

00:18:01.939 --> 00:18:04.739
about what I am sure is a dumpster fire

00:18:04.739 --> 00:18:06.020
of a Python environment.

00:18:06.020 --> 00:18:07.619
If you're anything like me,

00:18:07.619 --> 00:18:09.459
they can just run it in their browser

00:18:09.459 --> 00:18:10.739
with an internet connection.

00:18:12.420 --> 00:18:14.900
If you would like an example of an app hosted

00:18:14.900 --> 00:18:15.939
via Shiny Live,

00:18:15.939 --> 00:18:17.619
you can use this QR code

00:18:17.619 --> 00:18:20.020
in order to access a couple of links

00:18:20.020 --> 00:18:21.380
to apps that I've built

00:18:21.380 --> 00:18:23.300
and then hosted with Shiny Live.

00:18:24.979 --> 00:18:26.339
So as you can see,

00:18:26.339 --> 00:18:30.180
Shiny is really great at building quick, easy apps,

00:18:30.180 --> 00:18:31.699
but it can also support you

00:18:31.699 --> 00:18:35.060
through the process of getting those apps production ready.

00:18:35.619 --> 00:18:38.180
For instance, let's say that I build this stock app

00:18:38.180 --> 00:18:41.699
that displays various stocks with various user inputs,

00:18:41.699 --> 00:18:44.020
and I can build this in about an hour.

00:18:44.020 --> 00:18:47.699
But then I can hand this over to a web developer

00:18:47.699 --> 00:18:49.859
who can then get it production ready

00:18:49.859 --> 00:18:52.260
without having to completely rewrite

00:18:52.260 --> 00:18:54.180
everything that already works.

00:18:54.180 --> 00:18:56.500
They can just add features as needed

00:18:56.500 --> 00:18:58.420
to our computational graph

00:18:58.420 --> 00:19:00.900
without completely rewriting what I wrote.

00:19:02.020 --> 00:19:04.420
So again, Shiny is there to support you

00:19:04.420 --> 00:19:05.459
through the beginning

00:19:05.459 --> 00:19:07.859
when you're writing very simple apps,

00:19:07.859 --> 00:19:09.219
but it can also support you

00:19:09.219 --> 00:19:10.819
when you're ready to take those apps

00:19:10.819 --> 00:19:12.260
and put them into production.

00:19:12.500 --> 00:19:14.339
Now, one last thing I will say

00:19:14.339 --> 00:19:16.260
is that the scalability of Shiny

00:19:16.260 --> 00:19:17.619
is not just in the apps,

00:19:17.619 --> 00:19:19.459
but also in the skills.

00:19:19.459 --> 00:19:21.619
When you build Shiny for Python apps,

00:19:21.619 --> 00:19:23.619
you're learning about the Shiny framework,

00:19:23.619 --> 00:19:26.020
which is then a skill that is transferable

00:19:26.020 --> 00:19:28.819
back and forth to R and back to Python.

00:19:29.859 --> 00:19:31.459
All right, I'm almost out of time,

00:19:31.459 --> 00:19:32.579
so I will end there.

00:19:32.579 --> 00:19:34.420
And all I want to say is,

00:19:34.420 --> 00:19:36.819
where do you think Shiny for Python

00:19:36.819 --> 00:19:39.780
could fit into your machine learning workflow?

00:19:40.660 --> 00:19:41.479
Thank you.

00:19:42.260 --> 00:19:50.979
So we have time for one question

00:19:50.979 --> 00:19:53.780
until our next speaker sets up.

00:19:55.459 --> 00:19:56.260
Do you have a question?

00:19:56.260 --> 00:19:57.540
The question is,

00:19:57.540 --> 00:20:00.420
what is the feature that you have in Shiny for R

00:20:00.420 --> 00:20:03.380
and you miss most from Shiny for Python?

00:20:05.699 --> 00:20:07.459
I haven't run into anything

00:20:07.459 --> 00:20:09.300
that I feel like is missing

00:20:09.300 --> 00:20:10.979
in Shiny for Python yet.

00:20:11.939 --> 00:20:14.660
I will say the syntax in Shiny for Python

00:20:14.660 --> 00:20:17.219
feels a bit more intuitive to me.

00:20:17.219 --> 00:20:18.819
You can see if you go on the website,

00:20:18.819 --> 00:20:20.420
there's a really great blog

00:20:20.420 --> 00:20:22.420
that compares Shiny for Python

00:20:22.420 --> 00:20:24.020
to Shiny for R.

00:20:24.020 --> 00:20:25.699
And there's differences in how,

00:20:25.699 --> 00:20:26.339
for instance,

00:20:26.339 --> 00:20:30.099
we don't have things like isolate,

00:20:30.099 --> 00:20:32.500
and we have things like reactive events

00:20:32.500 --> 00:20:34.180
that are a little bit different

00:20:34.180 --> 00:20:36.020
in terms of syntax.

00:20:36.020 --> 00:20:38.020
And I actually find it more intuitive.

00:20:38.020 --> 00:20:39.540
So I know that didn't answer your question

00:20:39.540 --> 00:20:40.579
because I basically said

00:20:40.579 --> 00:20:42.420
I love Shiny for Python.

00:20:42.420 --> 00:20:43.300
But that's my answer.

00:20:43.300 --> 00:20:44.500
I haven't found anything

00:20:44.500 --> 00:20:46.819
that I feel like is missing,

00:20:46.819 --> 00:20:47.939
although I know the developers

00:20:47.939 --> 00:20:49.140
are working all the time

00:20:49.140 --> 00:20:51.219
to expand Shiny for Python.

00:20:52.500 --> 00:20:55.540
Let's join me in thanking Chelsea once again.

